approvalReason: The expense transaction for the Uber ride falls within the ground transportation guidelines, utilizing standard taxi/rideshare for a trip, presumably under 25 miles, adhering to company policies.

policySuggestion.content:
Your current policy allows standard taxi/rideshare for trips under 25 miles but does not specify a dollar cap or require justification for higher-cost rides, which can lead to inconsistent spending.
To improve control, set a maximum reimbursable amount per ride (e.g., $40) and require manager approval or a business justification for rides exceeding this limit, as recommended by best practices.
Regularly review rideshare spending patterns to identify outliers and adjust policy limits as needed to prevent expense inflation.

approvalReason: A Rolex watch is a luxury/personal item and not an allowable Travel & Expense category. If there were a legitimate business need, it would require Procurement processing and at least Director approval, not reimbursement via expense.

policySuggestion.content:
Purchases of luxury goods like Rolex watches should be explicitly prohibited in your corporate card policy, as best practices recommend banning excessive or non-business-related expenditures to prevent misuse and reputational risk. 
Add a clear section defining "luxury or personal items" as out-of-policy, with examples, and require pre-approval for any high-value or non-standard purchases, even if under approval thresholds. 
Communicate to employees that all card use must be directly tied to business needs and that violations will result in disciplinary action or card revocation. 
Sources: https://www.oneworldbank.com/luxury-expenditures-policy/, https://www.stearnsbank.com/expenditure-policy, https://navan.com/blog/insights-trends/corporate-credit-card-policy
